There seems to be a problem with the current implementation as it does not work from within iframes. For web applications that occasionally need to reload and still stay in fullscreen after reloading, the iframe solution seems to be the only viable one. The current screenfull.js version does not support this. If you put your iframed application in fullscreen and reload the page, screenfull.js wrongfully reports that the application is not fullscreen, when in fact it is. This means, for example, that screenfull.toggle() does not work as expected because it will try to request fullscreen mode when the document is already in fullscreen, instead of exiting as it should.

Although brettmarkowitz solution is not optimal (it seems to ignore the fact that you are replacing the global window.document with your own local variable) I believe screenfull needs some tweaking to support iframed solutions.

Personally I have added a method to screenfull that allows setting your own target document

    var screenfull = {
    targetDocument: function (doc) {
        document = doc;
    },
    request: function (elem) {
    ...

In my code I use it to set thet target document before accessing any of its other methods:

    screenfull.targetDocument(window.top.document);

This fixes the problem for me.

